                        expecting new people and new methods. [...] It would be appropriate that
                        times would be set aside for Gaelic speakers in the schools – not to teach
                        them language, but to pass on knowledge to them on history, on music, on the
                        form and the lifestyle of the world at large, on any subject that is
                        suitable and useful to schoolchildren – through Gaelic. On the subject of
                        music, shouldn’t the BBC be a step ahead of the rest, producing new methods
                        and forms, without neglecting the valuable things that are in our
                        inheritance? They have to keep an eye on old age and on the youth, and we
                        are not without hope that they will pull back part of Gaelic-speaking youth
